{% block content %}
<h2>Seals</h2>

<h3>Introduction</h3>

<p>
Seals are marine mammals that spend most of their lives in aquatic
environments. They belong to the pinniped family and are found in oceans all
around the world.
</p>

<h3>Adaptation to marine life</h3>

<p>
Seals possess streamlined bodies and powerful flippers that allow them to move
efficiently in water. Their thick layer of fat protects them from cold
temperatures and serves as an energy reserve.
</p>

<h3>Feeding habits</h3>

<p>
The diet of seals mainly consists of fish, squid and other marine organisms.
Many species are exceptional divers and can remain underwater for extended
periods while searching for food.
</p>

<h3>Relationship with their environment</h3>

<p>
Seals play an important role in marine ecosystems. They participate in the
balance of food chains and are considered indicators of environmental health in
many regions of the world.
</p>
